CatDescriptText: Cutline of related image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, March 10, 1962, pg. 12 reads: "Spark NAACP Benefit - Watching attentively as Jack Reynolds (far left) gives them a preview of his act as "The African Story TEller," are members of the committee sponsoring the NAACP benefit program. "Know Your Heritage," on March 18, at Ebenezer Baptist Church.   Left to right are: (seated) Elnora Harvey, Mrs. Marlene Moore, Johnathan K. Tyler and Patricia Adams.  Standing: Mrs. Lorenda Tyler, Alfred Herbert and Dorothy K. Williams, NAACP youth director.  The sculptured figure in foreground is Thaddeus Mosley's "impressions of Dizzy." - Harris Photo."
TitMainTitle: Jack Reynolds wearing African style dress with feathers, standing beside Thaddeus "Thad" Mosley sculpture "Impressions of Dizzy," in front of, seated: Elnora Harvey, Marlene Moore, Johnathan K. Tyler, and Patricia Adams; standing: Lorenda Tyler, Alfred Herbert, and Dorothy K. Williams, in Loendi Club
